On March 7, 2024, one (1) defective 275-gallon tote of UN1760 leaked approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior during transit. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the release and worked them in with hand tools. A forklift was utilized to perform a gravity transfer of the remaining product from the damaged 275-gallon tote into one (1) new 275-gallon tote. Additional granular absorbents were deployed to the trailer floor to remove any remaining material and worked in with hand tools.  All UN1760-impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) 35-gallon drum for disposal.

column169: On 03/28/2024, at 1745 hours, personnel in the CSXT Maxwell Yard discovered WCHX 30209, a loaded  tank car of acetone, leaking from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Ineos Phenol Inc, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2024032800201). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found three of four bolts on the liquid line valve mounting flange were less than tool tight. Contractor personnel tightened the liquid line flange bolts to stop the release and decontaminated the residue material from the side of the tank car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Marcelles Prather, Marcelles.Prather@Ineos.com, 251-463-6082).  The car was held out of  Transporation pending additional repair by a certified repair shop or One Time Movement Approval from FRA.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: SkyWest Airlines was notified via an Irregular Operations Report of a PED fire/incident that occurred on SkyWest 5079 SHR-DEN on 3/30/24 (CRJ 200/N465SW).  The incident occurred prior to boarding in SHR. A passenger’s checked bag was loaded into the cargo pit. The ramp agent loading the bags inside the pit noticed smoke coming from the passenger’s bag. The bag was immediately removed from the aircraft and taken to a safe location.  Airport Fire and Rescue was notified and responded. Fire rescue crews neutralized the smoking bag. The passenger was then brought into a private room to speak with TSA and the station’s supervisor on duty to discuss the battery fire. According to the IOR report, it was determined, at that point, that the cause of the smoke was a charger charging what appears to be a battery tray holding possibly four 18650 lithium Ion Batteries. The charred battery/charging device is currently being held by the Airport Fire and Rescue in SHR.  I asked the station manager if he could tell if it was a charging device actively charging a battery in the checked bag. The best he could tell, because of the charred nature of the devices, that there may have been a e-cigarette charger that was possibly charging batteries.

column169: From employee witness: During a cabin walk-through, I noticed a strong chemical smell. I could see a flight attendant speaking with a passenger in the aisle of the B zone cabin. They were standing next to a Polaris seat with a flashlight. I immediately asked the flight attendant what was happening, and where the smell was coming from. He showed me a broken cell phone belonging to 12A Norris Dodson. From what I was told, Mr. Dodson woke sometime prior and realized his phone was no longer on his person. He notified flight attendant and asked for help in retrieving it. In the process of searching for the phone, flight attendant activated the electronic seat controls. The phone was crushed by the mechanism and the lithium battery was punctured. When I arrived at the seat, the phone was hot to the touch. There was no smoke, or any other indicator of fire. But to be safe, between the chemical smell and the heat of the phone, I decided to place the phone in the thermal containment bag. The pilots were notified, and the information was sent to Ground staff.

column169: On March 28, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of sodium hydroxide had a leaking bung and released approximately twenty-five (25) gallons of product to the loading dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the impacted site. HES closed the valve on the nozzle completely which halted the leak. HES placed a zip tie on the valve to prevent further accidental opening. All impacted absorbents and debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and staged onsite. The drum containing liquid product was labeled as hazardous waste and staged onsite for disposal.

SequenceEvent: The damaged hazmat was placed in a red hazardous material bin on the hazmat pallet in QA. There was a small pool of liquid in the red hazardous bin that leaked from the container. XPO Logistics terminal XCN experienced a UN2522 Visiomer Madame release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 12-ounces of product released to a 2’ x 6” area of the metal drum lid/body. The release was due to the drum having the incorrect bung cap placed on it. The bung was replaced with a new one and secured for shipment on. The impacted drums were wiped down with absorbent pads which were then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: A Veolia employee was unloading drums from a trailer at Veolia's ten day intransit facility in Azusa, CA. The employee used a forklift with a drum grabber attachment to pick up the 55 poly drum by it's lip. Prior to moving the drum, the drum appeared to be in good condition as there was no visible deficiencies identified by the forklift operator. Once the employee began to back up the drum, the drum lip broke off causing the drum to fall and break. Approximately 20 gallons was released onto the trailer and cement floor (all in secondary containment). The spill was immediately cleaned up.   After investigating the incident, Veolia believes that the plastic was brittle but unfortunately, we are not sure of the cause of the brittleness since the site only utilizes a few of these drums.
column170: Veolia has reached out to the shipper to verify with their drum vendor in regards to the condition of the drum. In addition, Veolia made some recommendations to the shipper regarding proper storage and inventory management to potentially reduce this from a future occurrence. Lastly, Veolia employees who pick up drums from this site have been notified/trained to verify the container integrity.

Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted the 150-gallon poly tote and the contractor was unable to determine the volume of material released due to a forklift puncture of one (1) 150-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel stated that they believed that some of the released material evaporated. Hepaco personnel transferred the remaining material into a new poly tote and generated one (1) 55-gallon poly drum containing the cut-up poly tote, impacted absorbents and PPE. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal NNC experienced a battery acid release from a 2500-pound UN2794 battery. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of battery acid released to a 4’ x 15’ area of the trailer floor and a 11’ x 54’ area of the concrete lot below due to a load shift. The battery was re-secured for shipment on. Sodium bicab and baking soda were deployed and worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the release. All impacted absorbents and PPE were containerized into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On March 11, 2024, two (2) 5-gallon pails of UN2054 were damaged during transit due to lack of dunnage and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the UN2054 impacted trailer floor and neutralized the product on the pallet. FCE deconstructed the pallet and restacked the remaining intact freight for further transport. All spent absorbents and neutralized debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon metal open-top drum for further handling. The two (2) damaged metal pails were placed into one (1) 55-gallon metal open top drum for disposal.

column169: SequenceEvent: Metal drum was at the rear terminus of moving NC belt, the weight of the oncoming packages forced a protruding metal rod from another package to impact the drum, puncturing it and forcing it over the side of the belt onto the floor below. Punctured drum was placed in a hazmat bag lined tote, spreading spill on floor was contained using absorbent tubing, spilled material was squeegied into containment zone and mopped up using absorbent pads. DescribePack: Metal drum was punctured on the side about an inch or beneath the top lid of the drum. The puncture runs about an inch in length, between an 8th and a 1/4 inch in width. In addition, wet label and denting on other side of drum suggestive of a very small crack, likely the result of the impact with the floor. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: Area was evacuated, Punctured drum was placed in a hazmat bag lined tote, spreading spill on floor was contained using absorbant tubing, spilled material was squeegied into containment zone and mopped up using absorbant pads. Fans used to disperse fumes.

SequenceEvent: UNLOAD MANAGER CAME TO QA AT ABOUT 5AM AND INFORMED QA THERE WAS A HAZMAT DAMAGE AT ONE OF THE UNLOAD BAY DOORS. QA IMMEDIATELY WENT OVER THERE AND INSPECTED THE AREA AND LUCKILY THERE WASNT ANY AFFECTED SURFACE AREAS IN THE TRAILER, HOWEVER, FIVE BOXES WERE SPILLED ON. THE UNLOAD MANAGER PUT THE DAMAGED HAZMAT INTO A HAZBAG AND QA PUT IT INTO A LINED BIN AND IT WAS BROUGHT OVER TO THE QA TABLE FOR PROCESSING. DescribePack: AT FIRST GLANCE THERE WAS A WET SPOT ON THE SIDE OF THE BOX BUT NO OTHER SIGNS OF DAMAGE. WHEN QA OPENED THE PACKAGE THERE WAS A 2.5 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLE OF CONCENTRATED LIQUID DISHMACHINE DETERGENT THAT HAD A LOOSE CAP AND HAD SPILLED ONTO THE SLOTTED PARTITION THAT WAS USED TO BRACE IT. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE DAMAGED HAZMAT WAS QUICKLY PUT INTO A HAZBAG AND THEN PUT INTO A LINED BIN. THE SPILLED ON PACKAGES WERE REMOVED AND PUT ON THE SPILL TRAY AND COLLECTED AFTER THE HAZMAT WAS SAFELY MOVED TO THE QA TABLE.

Technical name Sodium Hydroxide) have leaked a small amount of the contents out of the package. Some of the box is wet due on the exterior but that is rain that has soaked a portion of the packaging. Upon closure inspection the caps were loose, and the corrosive liquids were observed to originate at the affected area. None of the liquid contents from inside of the package has been released out of the box, but still leaked from the inner jugs. No inner packing was found inside of the package. DescribePack: The Jugs were observed to have no leaks upon discovery, but some of the liquid inside of the container was out of the container and was at the time of discovery staining the inner exterior box. The caps enclosing the jugs containing the corrosive solution were observed to be loose with the most recently escaped liquid appearing right below the cap. The caps on the containers were promptly tightened and no leaks were observed after test and observing for a leak. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Upon awareness of the damaged hazmat, the caps were tightened prevent any further leaks.

PVS Transportation driver was scheduled to deliver a shipment of Sodium Bi Sulfite to City of Atlanta. Once the driver arrived on site he proceeded to the unloading location and met with the onsite representative. The onsite representative directed the driver to hook up to tank#1 connection. The driver hooked up to the unloading connection and proceeded to make the delivery. During the delivery the driver the driver was standing outside near his trailer connection and noticed a sound that didn' t represent offload and went to investigate. Upon investigation the driver noticed the unloading line wasn' t connected to the tank and the driver proceeded back to his truck to shut off the product flow. Approximately 300 gallons of Sodium Bisulfite was released into containment.
column170: Transportation driver on the importance of reviewing the tank prior to offloading and ensuring the correct product label is on the tank and any issues before making the delivery. Also, discuss in the employee engagement meeting the importance of walking the line, observing hazards, and utilizing stop work authority

XPO Logistics terminal XKC experienced a UN3266 Flash Clene 1414 release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. column59: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column169: On 3/30/2024, at 11:12 hours, personnel in the CSXT Atkinson Yard in Madisonville, KY, reported GATX93341, a loaded tank car of Fluorosilicic Acid leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Simplot Phosphates, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #20240330-00051). Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the release was due to a faulty pressure relief device; the vent assembly was found with no rupture disc, surge protection sleeve, or rupture disc retaining ring.  Additionally, the threads utilized for installing a rupture disc retention ring into the assembly base were broken.   MEI personnel removed the faulty pressure relief device and replaced with an in-kind assembly to temporarly secure the car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Anthony Guillen 208-780-0794).  The car was held out of transportation at Madisonville, KY pending additional repair by a certified car shop.

column169: SequenceEvent: Packaged Handlers were unloading a van that had the Hazmat. The Hazmat was toppled over when found and was leaking some of the chloride inside (solid). Package Handlers contacted an Ops Manager and informed QA/Coordinator of the incident. We removed the packaged from the vehicle and put it in a bucket to keep spilling anymore of the contents inside the station. It was taken to the Hazmat cage where upon further inspection found that the Hazmat material was inside of a plastic cylinder (outer container is a cardboard box). While transferring the leaking Hazmat, it was found that the bottom of the cylinder had cracked and was leaking a massive amount of the chlorine. The box itself was already filled halfway with the leaking contents. Admins wore protective gloves and used the ventilation shaft to not inhale the "fumes" of the chloride. The Hazmat was placed in a Hazmat container and DPR/ISF were filled out. DescribePack: The packaged appeared to have been repacked as it has a new label and was missing the shipping documents and had lots of tape wrapped around the closures. Looking at the photos from previous stations before it's arrival to the current one, it was in a much nicer box with better taping/packaging. The bucket likely could have been dropped at some point during it's transport casuing the bottom portion to be cracked, or likely from moving around inside the box as it did not have any filling inside to prevent the contents from moving around. The driver also could have secured the package to stop it from sliding around on the floor, perhaps had it on one of the shelves. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: Hazmat was removed immediately from the van and into a bucket in order to take it to the hazmat cage.

column169: At approximately 17:45hrs 3/12/2024, Southeastern Freight Lines employee attempted to load the Outbound shipment onto trailer 289184F located in dock door 35. While loading a protruding piece of wood punctured the 250 gallon tote of UN2922 product. This caused approximately 50 gallons of the product to spill in the Southeastern trailer & on the dock. The tote was maneuvered on its side immediately in efforts to stop the spillage. Containment boom, absorbent pad, & floor dry were used in additional efforts to contain the spill. None of the chemical was near or entered any type of drain system. Southeastern Freight Lines Safety was notified approximately at 17:50hrs. Hazmat 1 was notified approximately at 18:01 hrs. LA State Police & E3/OMI Environmental arrived approximately between 19:30 -20:00hrs. After accessing the situation at hand, E3/OMI Environmental proceeded to pump the waste chemical from the damaged tote into a new tote. They also cleaned & decontaminated the affected area. All clean up efforts concluded approximately at 02:00hrs. E3/OMI will coordinate the pick up of the following: 1-empty 250 gallon tote, 1-300 gallon tote, 4-55 gallon drums with clean up, 1-bag of contaminated pallets & packaging materials, & 1 bag w/ contaminated wooden crate.

On March 13, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1903 was damaged by falling freight and released approximately four (4) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath the trailer. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the UN1903-impacted trailer and concrete. All impacted material was collected and containerized into three (3) 35-gallon drums and the patched tote was placed on a spill pallet. All waste was staged in the R+L heat room for transport and disposal. The crew returned the next day to perform a tote transfer. TLE personnel transferred the product from the damaged 330-gallon tote into a new 375-gallon tote to be shipped off to its destination. The generated waste from the transfer was collected and containerized into one (1) 15-gallon poly drum. All waste and the damaged tote was staged in the R+L heat room for transport and disposal.

The driver of the vehicle was driving at approximately 60 mph when he felt a drop on the backend of the vehicle.  At that time, the driver lost control of the vehicle and began to fishtail and then the vehicle rolled onto its top. A  witness to the incident informed the driver that he had lost his back passenger wheels off the truck in transit and this caused the loss of control. It was determined that the wheel studs had completely broken off causing this to happen. The wreck and rollover are what caused the damage to the packaging of the chemicals. The duration of the release was approximately 45 minutes. Creedence immediately contacted an emergency response hazmat  clean up crew and got them to the location of the incident. They immediately began containing the spill from spreading and cleaning what had been spilt. Creedence notified the National Response Center of the spill and  TCEQ was on site directing the clean up the following day.
column170: An internal review of the vehicle's maintenance history was completed. The vehicle had recalls on  wheel studs that were inspected and approved by a dodge dealership maintenance shop 5 days before the  incident took place. A second shop, located a broken wheel stud while performing other maintenance the day following the studs being inspected and approved by the first shop. The broken stud was on the driver side wheel, opposite side of the studs  that sheered off causing the incident. This stud was replaced. This oversight indicates the inspection that  approved all wheel studs was negligent. Following the incident, Creedence shut down all vehicles with the same  recall and grounded them until the wheel studs were replaced, and not simply inspected.

A pallet of Aldahol was shipped on a local service truck to Veolia's ten day intransit facility in Philadelphia, PA. Upon opening the service truck to offload the materials, the facility crew noted a pallet of items that had broken apart during transportation. Cardboard boxes were no longer secured to the pallet with some on their sides with obvious signs of leakage from the inner packages.  An investigation revealed the stretch-wrap securing the boxes to the pallet failed during transportation due to heavy containers stacked on top of lighter weight containers. The pallet was not sufficiently wrapped to secure the boxes for transportation.  Trained Veolia facility employees removed the stretch wrap and upright the packages. The leaking packages were overpacked and the material was repalletized appropriately. The stretch wrap was wrapped to the pallet of containers utilizing a mechanical means to ensure proper stretch wrap tension and securement to the pallet.
column170: Veolia transport crews are being retrained on inspecting and properly preparing pallets of stretch-wrapped material for shipments.

column169: Driver was traveling north bound on I-75 north of Flint, MI when he was pulled over by Michigan State Police at 16:15 ET for a lane restriction violation. Upon inspection of the tractor/trailer, the trooper detected a leak coming out from under the ss skin on the bottom of the trailer just in front of the rollover protection. A tub was placed underneath the leak to contain it until the cleanup crew from Michigan Spill Response arrived on scene. After a short period of time, the leak stopped and there was only residue on the trailer. At that time, the top of the trailer was visually inspected and right above the area of the leak, there was a 3" washout cap that had fresh residue in the area which indicated that it had leaked. When Michigan Spill Response arrived on scene, they went to the top of the trailer and determined that the front washout cap was loose. They removed the washout cap, inspected the gasket, and then secured the washout cap to the threaded connection. After replacing the cap, a surge test was conducted on site and the trailer showed no signs of of any further leakage. Michigan Spill Response cleaned the residue from the trailer and disposed of the product that was collected in the catch pan placed underneath the trailer. Once the residue was removed rom the trailer, the load continued on without further incident. L
column170: Proper pre-trip inspection/washout cap securement to be addressed during monthly computer based training with all Martin drivers.

column169: A Veolia employee was driving a box truck loaded with a pair of totes and 15-20 55 gallon drums. Everything had been secured prior to leaving the customer's site with ratchet straps utilizing the e-track system in the truck. The road leaving the customer site grades down hill and as the driver was coming down hill he felt the load shift in the truck. The driver stopped at the stop sign at the bottom of the hill and exited the truck only to find that there was material leading from the front side of the truck cargo box. The totes had shifted and pulled the e-track away from the side of the truck, broke the clip that goes into the e-track, and slid forward in the cargo area of the truck, pushing a pallet jack into a poly drum filled with mostly water with trace amount of solvent. A corner of the pallet jack punched a hole in the poly drum releasing the contents out into the truck cargo area which left the truck and spilled on the road.   The Veolia driver called the local Fire Department to respond to the spill. WV DEP was on scene along with a third party ER group to clean up the material left on the road. The road was closed both directions for a period of time until clean up of the road and berm soil were complete. Note that after further investigation the drum that was damaged was over 96% water with trace amounts of organic compounds. This was not an RQ release that required reporting.
column170: Corrective actions included better load securement or leaving containers behind if they cannot be properly secured in the cargo area of the vehicle.

column169: At 18:00 Hours EST at the intersection of Ramsay Street and Main Street. A Wilbur-Ellis' driver out of the Tekoa, WA branch was cut off in traffic by third-party motorist, causing a shuttle to slide out of the back of a vehicle, resulting in strap failure and product shift. Approximately four (4) gallons of free product, Glypex 5 Herbicide, released to the roadway. There was no report of impact to soil. Nearest storm drain was approximately 100 yards from the spill site. Wilbur-Ellis' driver was able to contain the release using speedy-dry absorbent. Personnel from the Wilbur-Ellis' facility responded to the site and completed the cleanup. Waste was taken back to the facility to be disposed of via the facility waste stream.
column170: Since the release was accidental, no plans current exist to prevent recurrence. However, Wilbur Ellis will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site.  FCE personnel deployed absorbent pads and neutralizer to the nitric acid-impacted pallet and cardboard. All spent cardboard, pallet, absorbent pads and shrink wrap were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. An additional 55-gallon drum was used to over pack the damaged 2.2-liter jug. Both were set aside for terminal disposal.

column169: On March 18, 2024 at 2000 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Roadrunner personnel in Romeoville, IL regarding the release of approximately (1) quart of Ammonium Hydroxide Solution (Corrosive liquid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s., UN3266, 8, II) from (1) 5-Liter poly bottle. The total amount of 5 liter bottles in this shipment was unknown. Terminal personnel cleaned the original spill and needed a contractor to address the leftover residue on the surface. Contractors were dispatched and upon arrival clarified that the area that needed to be cleaned was not the original spill area, but a section of the OS&D area where some of this material was spilled when it was placed into the waste bucket. The impacted area initially pH tested around a 10-11 so contractors utilized Simple Green and Acid Gator to bring it down to a 7. All waste generated was containerized in (1) 55-gallon poly drum which was then staged onsite by contractors for proper disposal.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal LTU experienced a battery acid release from a 1750-pound UN2794 battery. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of product released to a 10’ x 20’ area of the wooden trailer floor due to improper loading/pallet failure. Absorbents and soda ash were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted area. The battery was up righted and re-secured for shipment on. All impacted absorbents, pallet wood, and PPE were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: SequenceEvent: As package was being placed onto a tugger in the Unload to be taken out to the Van Lines, a package handler said they thought they smelled a strange scent coming from packages on the cart and alerted QA. QA detected the smell was coming from this package and noticed small amount of outer packaging appeared wet from something inside, despite no other packages on pallet being wet. Upon determination, package was placed in red, lined hazmat tote and transported to processing area. No other packages found to be affected and upon opening Hazmat package (outer packaging then internal packaging containing regulated contents) determined the internal leakage was very minimal at time, all confined within inner and outer packaging. DescribePack: A cap on one of the two regulated containers within the inner packaging came loose somehow, resulting in a small internal leak of contents inside inner packaging w/ some product eventually seeping into outer packaging as well; all leaking was determined to be confined within inner and outer packaging, none on other packages or employees. No punctures or other signs/causes of leakage on any containers in package. Amount of leakage overall was very minimal. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The Unload team was quick to alert QA upon noticing the odor when package came off of trailer and on tugger cart. This enabled the responding QA to assess situation, place the hazmat in lined red tote, and get it moved from the sort to the hazmat processing area in a timely, safe, & efficient manner while being sure to follow necessary protocols and procedure. As such the release of product was confined to the package itself and outer spill/leakage was prevented.

column169: On 03/20/2024, during cruise phase of flight DL182 (JFK-FCO), a passenger identified a vape pen in a lavatory trash bin that was smoking. The flight attendant met with the captain, and they elected to remove the battery and place the vape pen into a containment bag. The captain then returned to the flight deck and contacted dispatch. A decision was made to continue to FCO as the vape pen had stopped smoking. No Flight Attendant or customer injuries were reported. The NRC and FAA were notified.

SHE NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR THAT IT WAS A LEAKING HAZMAT AND VERBALLY THE AREA WAS CORDONED OFF. SHE FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET ADDING SILVERSHIELD LINERS UNDER HER NITRILE GLOVES. SHE CONTAINERIZED THE BOX IN SPILL TUB. SHE PH TESTED THE FLOOR AS THERE WERE MULTIPLE STAINS ON FLOOR. THE PH WAS 9. SHE USED WATER AND A PAPER TOWEL TO NEUTRALIZE PH TO 7. SHE WIPED AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE. BECAUSE OF LENGTH OF STAINS, SHE CHECKED THE ROLLERS AND PACKAGES. ALL ROLLERS AND PACKAGES WERE CLEAN. DUE TO DAMPNESS AND TIME, SHE OBTAINED A CORRUGATED PIECE OF CARDBOARD TO COVER ENTIRE ALL STAINS ON THE FLOOR. SHE BROUGHT THE PACKAGE TO THE PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER AND FOLLOWED PROPER DMP PROCEDURE AND DISPOSITION OF PACKAGE.

column169: On March 28, 2024, four (4) 1-gallon cans of paint were crushed in transit and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Alpha-Omega Training Compliance (AOTC) to remediate the site. Crews downstacked the pallet to find the source of the release, and they found one (1) damaged cardboard box that contained four (4) 1-gallon cans had been crushed, so crews removed the box and its contents for waste. The product had leaked onto the outside of some of the other cardboard boxes, but the product had already dried. One (1) 55-gallon drum that contained the damaged cardboard box, four (4) impacted cans, and PPE was labeled and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

column169: From employee witness: During a cabin walk-through, I noticed a strong chemical smell. I could see a flight attendant speaking with a passenger in the aisle of the B zone cabin. They were standing next to a Polaris seat with a flashlight. I immediately asked the flight attendant what was happening, and where the smell was coming from. He showed me a broken cell phone belonging to 12A Norris Dodson. From what I was told, Mr. Dodson woke sometime prior and realized his phone was no longer on his person. He notified flight attendant and asked for help in retrieving it. In the process of searching for the phone, flight attendant activated the electronic seat controls. The phone was crushed by the mechanism and the lithium battery was punctured. When I arrived at the seat, the phone was hot to the touch. There was no smoke, or any other indicator of fire. But to be safe, between the chemical smell and the heat of the phone, I decided to place the phone in the thermal containment bag. The pilots were notified, and the information was sent to Ground staff.

On 03-05-2024 a CN transportation employee observed liquid running down the side of tank car from the top # UTLX 668009 at the CN Baton Rouge Yard located in Baton Rouge, LA. The employee reported the observation to the Transportation Manager who in turn initiated an emergency response from the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The on duty Dangerous Goods Officer dispatched an emergency response contractor to the yard to investigate. The responding contractor's initial observation found product residue on both sides of the tank car. Further assessment revealed that all (6) manway cover swing bolts were less than tool tight (could turn by hand) with (1) of the swing bolts in the down position causing a leak from the manway cover due to an improper seal of the gasket. The shipper security seal was found to be intact. The shipper manway cover security seal was removed and the cover was opened for the purpose of replacing the gasket. The manway cover swing bolts were then tightened in a star pattern utilizing an 18" pipe wrench. The tank car was then moved to an accessible track for the purpose of exterior cleaning.

While the shipment is classified as "nonhazard", the shipment began to emit dangerous evolution of heat, triggering an NRC notifciation.   On 3/15/2024 at approximately 2200, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 5013755 at the station location in Baton Rouge, reporting a package with a dangerous evolution of heat.  The shipment consisted of 12 ‘D’ cell batteries which, after further inspection, appeared to be swollen.  During delivery, the driver discovered the package was warm to the touch and returned it to the station.  This incident has been to be NRC under Report # 1393991 was generated by Ms. Rawls.  Due to the reporting requirements to the NRC, this shipment is also being reported to the FAA and is being held for further disposition instructions.

XPO Logistics terminal UKC experienced a UN1814 Potassium Hydroxide 45% release from (4) 55-gallon poly drums. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of product released to 6’ x 6’ area of the top of each poly drum. All four drums in shipment were found to have faulty bung caps, causing them to release. Each drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack after being wiped down. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The hose connection was leaking when the driver started his unload.  When they hook up they are to do a twist test on the hose to make sure it doesn't spin at all.  Any movement indicates either the gasket is bad or the camlocks that lock it down may need to be shimmed.  It did not twist when he tried moving it and the gaskets all looked good.  After he applied shims though it did stop the leak.  We're taking this hose out of use going forward and getting it back to the manufacturer so they can inspect it and replace the fitting on the end.  8 ounces hit the ground beyond the spill bucket.
column170: I do not believe any changes are needed for this event.  The hoses go through an annual inspection process which we maintain is a good cadence.  We do not typically see many hose incidents in a year related to the hook up fitting.

column169: The Union Pacific Railroad delivered TILX 202905 to the Minnesota Commercial Railway. During the inbound inspection, it was found that the car had some product coming out of the top when sloshing. No product was hitting the ground. The MNNR refused interchange on the railcar and notified the Union Pacific Railroad of the discovery. The Union Pacific hired Rybak Environmental Inc. to look at the car and clean up the side of the car. Upon inspection by Rybak, it was discovered that the car was missing a manhole gasket.
column170: Manhole gasket was installed by Rybak and secured.

Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 5ft-by-5ft area of the terminal concrete floor and estimated that one-hundred and thirty (130) gallons of material was released due to forklift damaging one (1) 275-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel transferred the remaining product from the damaged tote along with rinse water that was used to neutralize two (2) 85-gallon metal drums that Dayton terminal personnel used to collect the leaking product in prior to the contractor’s arrival. The rinse water was offloaded into one (1) 275-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted flooring and collected the spent absorbents and containerized it along with impacted debris into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred. Upon opening trailer to offload, a leak was discovered at nose of trailer. Area was isolated and ERLLC was dispatched to assess. Upon inspection of the trailer, ERLLC detected two(2) damaged 5-gallon pails. Apparently, the pails had fallen in transit due to improper blocking. Approximately 1 gallon of free product had released to the trailer floor. Less than 1 ounce had dripped to asphalt beneath trailer. ERLLC proceeded to clean trailer floor, overpacked the damaged pails into one 55-gallon overpack drum, and cleaned the affected asphalt. ERLLC returned the following day, offloaded shipment to gain access to entire trailer floor, and proceeded to clean trailer floor and wipe floor of all residual. Product was contained to immediate area, there was no threat or impact to state waters, and no further action was required.

First Call Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted an 8ft-by-3ft area of the asphalt lot and two (2) areas of the trailer floor measuring 8ft-by-15ft and 8ft-by-4ft and estimated that twenty-five (25) gallons of material was released due to forklift damaging one (1) 275-gallon poly tote. First Call Environmental personnel neutralized the impacted areas and the impacted wooden pallet and used absorbents to collect the material. The wooded pallet was broken down and placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted absorbents were recovered and containerized into two (2) 55- gallon poly drums. The remaining product in the damaged poly tote was transferred to a new tote and the damaged tote was cut up and placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: On 03/07/2024, at 1232 hours, personnel in the CSXT Walbridge, OH yard, discovered CHIU 258609, a loaded container of Waste Environmentally Hazardous Substance Solid N.O.S. (Benzene, Mercury UN3077 Class 9), leaking. The container was isolated and the shipper, Clean Harbors, notified. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the container leaking from the door seam.  It was presumed the release was due to a combination of an ineffective door seem and either a failure, or improper installation, of the box’s poly ethylene liner.  Contractor personnel secured the package by applying additional sealant to the rear door of the container.   The container was removed from the rail transportation and transported offsite via highway by the shipper.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Angel Villa 972-533-4154).

column169: A shipment of UN11G boxes of UN3175 Solids Containing Flammable Liquids was being transported from the shipping facility to end disposal when a release of approximately two pints of liquid occurred. The release was a result of a compromised inner liner. The liquid released through the van trailer floor and approximately one pint impacted the gravel below. The release was discovered while transferring the trailer's contents and was contained with absorbents. The leaking container was wrapped in non-permeable plastic sheeting before being moved into concrete secondary containment and re-packaged. The initial absorbents were containerized, any remaining residue was absorbed with kitty litter and all spill response debris was containerized for off site management. The impacted soil was containerized and a background sample was taken. Sample results confirmed all spill residue was recaptured and removed. All solid and liquid waste generated was shipped off-site for disposal.
column170: Retraining has been provided to the packaging team to ensure that solid and liquid material for shipment are packaged appropriately. The incident was also reviewed at the Safety Improvement Committee meeting with all hands.

column43: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column169: On March 8, 2024 at 5:36am, an AutoZone tractor trailer had the trailer tires go onto a rain softened shoulder causing the tractor trailer to jack knife and ultimately rollover onto the passenger side of the vehicle.  During the rollover, the last pallet on the driver side of the trailer (with an electric pallet jack under it) fell on the last pallet on the passenger side of the trailer that contained 24 automotive batteries.  The weight of the pallet and pallet jack cracked the plastic case of 10-12 of the batteries releasing approximately 1.2 gal. of battery acid (sulfuric acid) per battery.  The acid did start leaking from the trailer until after the tractor and trailer were uprighted were in the process of returning to the roadway.  The plastic wrapped pallet containing the batteries contained the leak until the pallet was returned to the upright position and then the acid began leaking through the pallet.  The onsite towing company had a response team come and contain the spill, dispose of the damaged batteries and remediate the affected soil.
column170: The plastic wrapped pallet of batteries contained the spill until uprighted.  The wrapped pallet also protected almost half of the batteries on the pallet from damage.  The circumstances that caused the damage were unfortunately from the unforseen vehicle rollover.

column169: On March 26, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of paint was punctured by a forklift and released approximately thirty (30) gallons of product to the trailer interior and one (1) gallon to the underneath of the trailer. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted site. LSH patched the metal drum and placed it into one (1) 95-gallon poly overpacked drum. LSH personnel deployed granular absorbents to the interior of the trailer and pavement below to absorb the paint. LSH swept all paint impacted absorbents with hand tools and containerized them to one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. Utilizing degreaser, LSH wiped off impacted surfaces of the cargo shipment and contained all remaining debris absorbent pads and utilized PPE into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. LSH generated two (2) 55-gallon poly drums worth of non-hazardous waste, and one (1) 95- gallon overpacked poly drum of hazardous waste. All waste generated was labeled appropriately and staged onsite for further handling.

Upon arrival, free product was detected on the warehouse floor, and contained to immediate area. Green Charge utilized absorbent material and recovered all product. The damaged drum was overpacked to prevent further incident. Spent absorbents were placed into one 55-gallon drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

On March 14, 2024, two (2) 55-gallon drums of UN3098 were punctured by a forklift and released approximately twenty (20) gallons of product to the trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews utilized duct tape to patch the damaged drums to prevent additional release. TLE crews collected and containerized the damaged drums into two (2) 95-gallon overpack drums for disposal purposes. Soda ash was deployed worked in with hand tools.  A granular absorbent and a degreasing agent were deployed and worked in with hand tools. All undamaged cargo was wiped with absorbent pads to remove any residual product and repalletized for continued processing and shipping. All impacted materials were collected and containerized in one (1) 35-gallon drum for disposal purposes. Soda ash was deployed to neutralize the impacted outside the concrete ground and worked in with hand tools. All impacted materials were collected and containerized in one (1) additional 35-gallon drum for disposal purposes.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: AT 14:05 LOCAL TIME IN HONG KONG, AIR PACKAGE 1Z8Y202X0464721146 HAD PASSED X-RAY SCAN WHEN  A LOADER OBSERVED THE PACKAGE SMOLDERING ON THE BELT. THIS OCCURRED PRIOR TO LOADING INTO AN AIR CONTAINER. A RESPONDER SEGREGATED AND INSPECTED CONTENTS TO FIND A THERMAL EVENT OCCURRING WITH THIRTEEN OF THE LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INSIDE THE PACKAGE. AT 14:17 LOCAL TIME AIR PACKAGE 1Z8Y202X0466413289 WHICH WAS TRAVELING UNDER THE SAME MULTI-PIECE SHIPMENT WAS FOUND SMOLDERING AFTER HAVING ALREADY BEEN LOADED INTO AN AIR CONTAINER. PACKAGE CONTENTS WERE INSPECTED TO FIND EIGHT LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CHARRED INSIDE THE PACKAGE. LITHIUM ION BATTERIES IN BOTH PACKAGES INVOLVED IN THE THERMAL EVENT WERE ISOLATED. INSPECTION OF THE BATTERIES DO NOT INDICATE THE WATT HOURS. THE THERMAL EVENTS THAT OCCURRED INSIDE BOTH PACKAGES WERE ISOLATED TO THE LITHIUM ION BATTERIES ALONE. THERE IS NO EVIDENCE OF CHARRING ON THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOXES. THE PACKAGES WERE PART OF A 77 MULTI-PIECE SHIPMENT SCHEDULED TO TRAVEL FROM HONG KONG TO THE USA. THE PACKAGES HAD PREVIOUSLY PASSED AN ACCEPTANCE AUDIT. THE SHIPMENT WAS PREPARED IN ACCORDANCE WITH IATA PI 965 SECTION IA WITH A SHIPPERS DECLARATION, CAO LABELS, CLASS 9 LITHIUM BATTERY LABELS, MARKINGS AND OUTER UN SPECIFICATION PACKAGING. PER 49CFR 171.15, THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER UNDER REPORT 1393931.

Environmental Works was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 40ft-by-20ft area of the concrete terminal floor and estimated that one hundred and fifty (150) gallons of material was released due to forklift damaging one (1) poly tote. Environmental Works personnel deployed a neutralizer and then a granular absorbent to the impacted area. The remaining material was transferred to a new poly tote. The spent material was recovered and placed into three (3) 30-gallon poly drums, one (1) 55-gallon metal drum and one (1) 55-gallon poly drum along with the cut-up damaged poly tote. Environmental Works personnel then pressure washed the impacted area and collected the impacted water and containerized the recovered material into one (1) 330-gallon poly tote. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

On March 21, 2024, one (!) 275-gallon tote of UN3266 was damaged during transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. HCE personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the UN3266-impacted trailer floor. All impacted material was collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums and staged on site for transport and disposal. HCE personnel transferred the product from the damaged 275-gallon tote into a new 330-gallon tote

column169: On March 12, 2024 at 1421 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Orange, Texas regarding the release of approximately (225) gallons of FERRIC SULFATE SOLUTION, Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Inorganic, n.o.s. (UN3264, 8, III). Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors investigated and confirmed the release was caused by a load shift due to a hard brake and was contained to the trailer floor and a 100ft x 6ft area of asphalt trailing behind the unit. Contractors neutralized the release then used absorbents and the proper PPE to clean the release. Contractors were able to transfer the remaining product in the damaged tote to a new tote without complication. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (7) 55-gallon DF’s, which was then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal. **The NRC report has the city of Beaumont (which the spill took place in Orange City), this 5800 report was completed to match the NRC report for fluidity**

column163: SR. DIRECTOR OF SAFETY AND FIELD OPERATIONS
column169: Team Logistics Driver Eric Bell (Owner Operator 1099 Contractor) was making a bulk delivery of gasoline to Race Trac #232 on 1450 McEver Road, Gainesville, GA 30501. The delivery's inception; TransMontaigne Terminal on 3450 Jefferson Road, Athens, GA 30607 loading of Metroplex Energy. In route to the delivery on Highway 53 @ Hoyt Holder Road heading North, in Braselton, GA. Mr. Bell failed to maintain his lane of travel and rolled his tractor trailer. Mr. Bell stated, there were three vehicles in front of him traveling approximately 25 mph, and another vehicle turning right (South) from Hoyt Holder Road causing him to move toward the right shoulder. This movement brought Mr. Bells tires off the road and onto the soft, muddy shoulder. As Mr. Bell brought his tractor back onto the roadway the trailer entered a drop off area that turned the unit over. The tractor trailer rolled completely over with the tractor blocking both sides of Hwy 53, and the trailer positioned upside down arched between the road and the drop off area, slanting down about eight feet. Fortunately, Mr. Bell was able to evacuate the vehicle sustaining no injuries. Once out of the unit, Mr. Bell secured the scene making sure there were no hazardous materials compromising the environment. Jackson County Sheriff's Office and Fire Department were dispatched to the scene of the accident. GA DOT also was present to close Highway 53 off and to verify the hazardous cargo was not compromising the environment. GA DOT officer MCO Fortson conducted a DOT inspection on the vehicle following the FMCSA-inspection Platform (Driver/Vehicle Examination Report). Seymour's Towing and Recovery responded to the emergency for remediation and recovery. Team Logistics Emergency Team brought another tanker truck to transfer products. After conducting a safety briefing, a plan was put into place. The Jackson County Fire Department evacuated the three residents near the accident location for two hours during the transfer of product for safety, then set up a foam and water deployment location. Seymour's grounded and bonded the tanker for transfer, then secured the rolled unit with two wreckers.
column170: We wer-e then able to remove the bottom belly valves from the trailer to transfer the product safely. During the removal of the belly valves, approximately thirty-five gallons of gasoline were released into a protective berm containing booms and absorbents constructed before the transfer. Once all products were transferred, the tractor trailer was prepared for removal. Highway 53 was closed for five hours while the work was being conducted.  Further actions: Due to the inclement weather, polymer was placed over the impacted area and will be remediated by the weekend of March 22. Seymour's will be overseeing the remediation and disposal of all contaminated soil. No further actions are required.

On 03-21-2024 the CN Dangerous Goods Team was notified by a CN Transportation employee that an FRA Hazmat inspector observed liquid pooling around the Blind Flange of the Liquid line in the protective housing on Tank Car #UTLX 110020 while performing a regulatory compliance check at the CN Council Bluffs Yard in Council Bluffs, IA. A CN response contractor was dispatched to the yard to investigate. A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The CN contractor found that four (4) bolts on the Liquid Line blind flange were less than tool tight. The CN emergency response tightened the bolts, stopping the leak. The contractor observed the flange after tightening for 5 mins to ensure there was no further leakage from the flange. Protective housing was then secured using a HMRI security seal.
PACKAGE PROCESSED USING THE DECISION TREE FOR CORROSIVE LIQUIDS.

column169: On March 6, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1719 was crushed in transit due to lack of dunnage and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. column169: "11 packages were discovered in KSEA containing the following statement"Hazmat- Surface Transportation Only, Restricted E/ectronic Device." These 11 packages(see image below) did not include any of the DG markings or labels we train associates to detect(per ROC), but WFS nonetheless spotted and sidelined them. Had the packages not been sidelined, they would have been loaded onto ATI flight ATN3313(KSEA-PANC). The packages were non-AFN cargo, tendered and packaged by the shipper, Pitney Bowes. The sidelined packages in KSEA were opened to determine the exact content/product. All 11 of them contained Section Il lithium batteries in equipment, such as an ear cleaner, headsets, desk lamp, diving lamp. Of the 11, three were not labeled correctly: they contained rriultiple battery powered products, exceeding the two battery cell allowance for labeling exception. As a result, we consider these three packages to be undeclared DG, despite that they were not ultimately flown. Additionally, five of the 11 packages were packaged incorrectly: they were in a poly bag, not the corrugate box required by IATA PI 967/970. In terms of DOT reporting, per § 171.16"

column169: It was reported that approximately 150-gallons of gasoline were released impacting concrete and nearby soil. The spill occurred when the driver opened the drop head on his tanker trailer and accidentally overfilled it, causing approximately 150-gallons of gasoline to spill out. The driver deployed boom while waiting for assistance. The police and the fire department were notified and in route. The Fire Department responded and put down absorbents. The state of Mississippi was notified of the incident, but no report number could be provided by Catherine Bell. E3 Environmental arrived on site and swept-in absorbents solidifying released material on the impacted concrete. E3 Environmental scraped the surface of the impacted soil area and sprayed with microblaze. the impacted absorbents and soil were containerized into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum.

column169: Our truck was hauling a load of EAF dust from Nucor Crawfordsville, IN to deliver to WSP, Logansport, IN. He was traveling westbound on CR 225.  Another truck traveling eastbound on CR 225 was driving in the center of the road and ran our driver off the road, and then left the scene of the accident.  When our truck was run off the road, the truck and trailer overturned onto the passenger's side in a ditch.  Upon contact with the ground, the trailer body split and the manways on the roof came open released EAF Dust onto the ground.    *Included is a copy of the police report which includes a statement from a witness who saw it happen.
column170: We conduct Mandatory Quarterly Safety Meetings.  We cover all aspects of Safety with a focus on Defensive Driving as well as acute awareness of other motorists actions traveling the same roads as our drivers.  Our goal in doing so is to increase awareness and prevent accidents.  Additionally, we adhere to the DOT requirements for Haz Training and re-training.  After reviewing the circumstances of this accident, there was nothing within our control that could have prevented this accident.

At approximately 8:30 am, a OxyChem truck driver was delivering Caustic Soda to a customer site (Morehouse BioEnergy) located in Bastrop, LA. The driver met with the customer site operator, completed the “In the Interest of Safety Form” (which is a form utilized by OxyChem truck drivers to ensure that enough space exists in a customer tank prior to unloading), hooked up offloading hoses, and began offloading. Near the end of the offloading process, product began to overflow from the customer's storage tank into the containment area. The OxyChem truck driver immediately shut down the offloading process. The customer site operator was present with the driver when the overflow occurred and made a comment that they would have to check the tank level indicator for accuracy because the calculation during the completion of the “In the Interest of Safety Form” showed that there was sufficient capacity available within the storage tank. Customer site personnel washed down the area. The spill was estimated to be approximately 75-gallons. No injuries, property damage, or environmental impact as a result of the incident.
column170: The OxyChem truck driver immediately shut down the offloading operation and notified customer site operators. The area was washed down and cleaned up. Occidental Chemical Tech Service group has been requested to reach out to the customer site to discuss necessary corrections that are needed moving forward to prevent a re-occurrence. Proper repairs/replacement need to be completed to the level indicator on the product storage tank at the customer site.

column169: A Veolia employee was unloading the IBCs from a trailer at Veolia's ten day intransit facility and noticed that six out of the twelve bags had leaked inside the trailer. The waste was F039 filter cake that should have been all solid but instead had residual liquid left over from the process. Over time, the liquid settled out and leaked from the package. The liquid that leaked was absorbed with oil dry and the material was repacked before being shipped to the disposal facility.
column170: Veolia contacted the shipper of the waste regarding the leaking filter cake bags and advised that future shipments would not be accepted by Veolia until there is confirmation that the upcoming shipment will not contain any liquid in the filter cake, or a proper packaging approved for liquid will be used.

column169: At 6:55 am on 3/8/2024, Austin Powder drive was 4 miles south of Bismark MO at the intersect of N and NN.  He was negotiating a lefthand turn driving a 2019 KW T880, loaded with AN emulsion, and diesel fuel for manufacturing bulk products.  The drive swung too wide on a left hand turn and his passenger side went off the pavement.  The driver slowed to an almost stop.  The passenger side of the truck got stuck in the soft dirt and fell on its side.  20 pounds of AN spilled from one of the bins onto the ground.  Roughly 50 gallons of offroad diesel spilled from the truck as well.  The truck was put upright, and the AN spill was cleaned up and put into spill buckets and removed from the site.  The diesel spill was contained using socks and booms.  An environmental company came and removed the affected area at a later date.
column170: The driver was retrained on all aspects of vehicle handling, defensive driving, and a road test of approx. 45 mins was given.  The route to this customer was looked at to determine the safest route.

column169: On Friday March 1, 2024, N2278Z was operating from LAX to PIT. During the cruise phase of flight, a passenger's charging device(identified as a Cobra CPP8000 external lithium ion battery pack) began to smoke as a lithium battery runaway situation developed. The device was initially located within the passenger's carry-on backpack underneath the seat in front of them. Upon noticing the smoke, the passenger reached into their backpack for the battery pack and received second degree bums to their hands. The Inflight crew in partnership with a deadheading Breeze Captain suppressed the smoking device with water and utilized the onboard PED kit to contain the device. The flight diverted to KABQ out of an abundance of caution where it landed safely and was met by fire/EMS upon arrival at the gate. No evacuation was required and passengers were deplaned normally. The passenger who received burns was treated at the scene by EMS and released.
column170: Breeze's investigation found that all company processes and procedures were followed onboard the aircraft during the event. Some future actions to be taken are that the company will do its best to ensure that any devices that experience a thermal runway or quarantined under the control of the company upon arrival until the completion of any investigation.

UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE FOUND LARGE 3" DIAMETER TABLETS LINING TWO SIDES OF THE BOX AND A PLASTIC BIN INSIDE. THE PLASTIC BIN HAS AN OXIDIZER 5.1 YELLOW DIAMOND LABEL PRINTED ON ONE SIDE. THE LID SEAL ON THE BIN IS INTACT AND SEALED. THE LOOSE TABLETS AND SOME SMALL WADS OF NEWSPAPER LINE 2 SIDES OF THE BOX. THERE ARE NO LABELS ON THE USED OUTER CARTON, EXCEPT A PIECE OF PAPER TAPED ON BEARING THE NUMBERS 525D-619-010. CALLED THE HAZMAT HELP DESK AND SUBMITTED AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT REPORT. THIS PACKAGE WILL BE ENTERED INTO ETT AND HELD FOR INSPECTION.
